The code violates the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP). The SRP states that a class should have only one reason to change. In this case, both `GmailService` and `NotificationService` are responsible for sending emails, which is not ideal as it could lead to issues in the future if we need to change how emails are sent or received.

To refactor this code to comply with SRP, we can create a separate class that handles email sending:

```java
public interface EmailService {
    void sendEmail(String to, String subject, String body);
}

public class GmailService implements EmailService {
    public void sendEmail(String to, String subject, String body)  {
        System.out.println("Sending via Gmail: " + subject);
    }
}

public class NotificationService {
    private EmailService emailService;

    public NotificationService(EmailService emailService)  {
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }

    public void sendNotification(String to, String message)  {
        emailService.sendEmail(to, "Notification", message);
    }
}
```
In the refactored code, `GmailService` now implements an interface `EmailService` which has a single responsibility of sending emails. This allows us to change how we send emails without affecting the `NotificationService` class. For example, if we want to switch from Gmail to another email service in the future, we can simply create a new class that implements `EmailService` and pass it into the `NotificationService` constructor.

